column168: THE UNDERGROUND TANK THAT WE WERE UNLOADING INTO BECOME PRESSURIZED DUE TO A MECHANICAL FAILURE IN THE UNDERGROUND TANK. THIS PRESSURE CAUSED GASOLINE TO TRAVEL INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE DURING DELIVERY. THE SPILL OCCURED AT THE POINT IN WHICH THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE CONNECTS TO THE TRAILER BECAUSE THE DRIVER DIDN'T MAKE THE CONNECTION PROPERLY.
column169: WE WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND EDUCATE OUR DRIVERS ON THE PROPER, AND SAFE WAY TO UNLOAD INTO AN UNDERGROUND TANK.

column168: DRIVER TRAVELING NORTH ON US 23 IN VIRGINIA.WHILE COMING DOWN A HILL IN RAINY CONDITIONS.DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES.THE UNIT JACK-KNIFED,HIT A GUARD RAIL AND ROLLED MULTIPLE TIMES. WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO REST.PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM BOTH CLEAN-OUT CAPS.AND THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON TOP OF THE CHRISTMAS TREE.COUNTY EMS DIKED UP DITCH WITH BACKHOE TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM ENTERING ROADWAY AND WATERWAYS.COMPANY PERSONNEL REDUCED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT SUFFICIENT ENOUGH TO SAFELY TRANSFER LOAD TO ANOTHER UNIT.INCIDENT OCCURED AT APPROXIMATELY 1800.THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED BY 1830.THE TRAILER LEAKS WERE STOPPED BY 2200.THE LOAD BEGAN TO TRANSFER BY 0040.AND TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE BY 0300.
column169: THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN AND WILL CONTINUE TO BE COMMUNICATED TO ALL OF OUR PERSONNEL.WE INTEND TO USE IT AS A TRAINING TOOL FOR ACCIDENT AVOIDANCE.WE WILL CONTINUE TO FOCUS ON PROPER  DRIVING TECHNIQUES IN MOUNTAINOUS,AND INCLIMATE WEATHER CONDITIONS.WE WILL ALSO CONTINUE TO DISCUSS PROPER ATTITUDES TOWARD SAFETY,AND THE PHYSICS OF A LOADED TANK TRAILER DURING OPERATION.

column168: A van trailer was being moved from the 10 day storage yard to the warehouse of the intended waste disposal facility.  When opening the rear doors, the driver noticed a small amount of liquid dripping from the trailer.  The emergency response crew was notified, donned the appropriate PPE and placed the drum into a suitable salvage drum.  The interior and exterior of the trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning material, and the contaminated soil was placed into the salvage drum.  The material was then unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The origin location which loaded the trailer was advised of the situation.  Dock personnel were cautioned as to loading used drums against other objects in the load which could rub against drums causing leaks.

column168: A van trailer was to be transported from the 10 day storage yard to the intended waste disposal facility's warehouse.  The driver noticed a liquid had stained the ground and was leaking from the trailer.  He notified his supervisor who contacted the facility's emergency response crew who donned the appropriate PPE and entered the trailer when it was backed up to the dock.  The leaking drum was found to be corroded at the bottom causing the leak.  It was placed into a suitable salvage drum and the contaminated soil and absorbent material used to contain the spill were placed into a cubic yard box and disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound.
column169: The origin location was notified of the spill and the shipper and drivers involved were cautioned about the pickup of old corroded drums.

column168: While loading a shipment onto a van trailer at the 10 day waste transfer facility, the forklift drum grabber improperly grabbed the drum and popped off the removable lid, causing the drum to drop the the floor of the trailer.  The drum landed right side up, but the impact splashed approximately 4 gallons of liquid onto the floor of the trailer.  The facility's emergency response team was notified, they donned the appropriate PPE, contained the spill and applied a suitable absorbent material the the floor and the concrete below the trailer.  The drum and the material was placed into a salvage drum and loaded onto the trailer which had been cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound, where it proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility.  Louisiana State Police Haz Mat personnel were notified and assigned incident report number 09-00092 to the incident.
column169: Dock loading personnel were re-instructed to use caution when using the drum grabber to load drums onto trailers.

column168: A van trailer parked at the 72 hour storage lot of the intended waste disposal facility, was noticed to have a small wet spot on the concrete underneath.  The trailer was moved into the unloading bay and the emergency reponse team donned the appropriate PPE, entered the trailer and placed the drum into a suitable salvage drum.  The material on the trailer floor and the concrete was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material which was also placed into the salvage drum.  The drum was then taken to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The leak occurred due to corrosion of the drum.  The origin location was notified and they notified the shipper about using old used drums and employees about the importance of carefully checking old drums prior to acceptance.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading, one (1) carton containing one cylinder, containing approximately 77 gas cubic feet was damaged. Apparently the carton was placed on top of the forklift, and the forklift driver began to drive around.  The package fell from the top of the forklift, damaging the contents.  Approximately 77 cubic feet of free product were released and dissipated.  BAX Global, Inc, employee, Tom Priscal performed the cleanup using gloves.  The carton with entire contents was placed into a 55-gallon recovery drum  The drum will be returned to the shipper.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: At this time, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: *** Undeclared: Calcium Hypochlorite, Hydrated (UN2880) loaded ***    The shipment was booked with the following six (6) items of hazardous materials for loading on the Hapag-Lloyd Container Line vessel Bonn Express from Houston to Antwerp.    - UN1950, Aerosols, Class 2.1, Limited Quantity  - UN1950, Aerosols, Class 2.2, Limited Quantity  - UN1018, Chlorodifluoromethane, Class 2.2  - UN1956, Compressed Gas, NOS (Oxygen, Nitrogen), Class 2.2  - UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, NOS (Sodium Nitrite),     Class 9, PG III, Marine Pollutant  - UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, NOS (Copper), Class 9,     PG III, Marine Pollutant    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Houston of additional hazardous material (UN2880, Calcium Hypochlorite, Hydrated, Class 5.1, PG III) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Calcium Hypochlorite is prohibited by every ocean shipping line.

column168: Unloading the tank car at the SATCO facility using pressurized air and a 2" sulfuric acid discharge hose connected to the cars 2" siphon tube using camlock style fittings.  After the car is empty of liquid the large volume of air is then allowed to partially exit through the hose until the operator feels the car is completely empty.  This rush or air causes the flexible hose to shake and/or move which is normal.  After the operator observed the hose movement for a minute or so, and was about to close the valve, the locking ears on the camlock connection disengaged allowing the hose to disconnect from the top of the car.  This allowed the large volume of remaining air trapped inside the car to rapidly exit through the unobstructed 2" siphon tube on top of the car.  The air depleted within a few minutes and carried sulfuric acid mist with it.  The acid mist was carried by the wind and spread acid droplets onto the property next door contaminating pipeline, equipment, and a few automobiiles.  No personnel came into contact with the mist.  a contracted Environmental crew washed and neutralized all pipeline and equipment.  The automobiles are being repainted because of damage to the clear coat.
column169: The practice of using camlock style fittings to make the car connection has been eliminated.  The hose is now flanged to the car using 2" 150 lb stainless steel flanges.

column168: Our driver positioned the transport vehicle per plant operator's instructions.  The vehicle is outside ant the plant storage tanks are located in the building's  basement. Driver was given instructions to use his tractor mounted product pump and connect his product discharge hose to the customer's product receiving line.  Driver had all the necessary paperwork reviewed and signed by the plant operator. Driver was given permissoin by the operator to start the unloading of material.  Driver set the product pump at half pressure. The operator told driver the product was flowing good. The driver then set pump to the porper operating speed. As the trailer went empty, the operator informed the driver of the tank overfill. He also told the driver at that time that the product was split between four storage tanks and the piping is set up so the tanks fill at the same time and that one of the tanks had a higher level than the other three which led to the spill.
column169: This was a plant issue. our driver was out side of the building and had nothing to do with the customers storage tanks located in the basement of the building.  The operator signed our disclaimer conferming sufficient room in their storage tanks.  In speaking with the plant maintance manager, the operator was doing other things at the time of unloading and was bouncing between jobs and lost sight of the tank level.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: UTLX 210095 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported sloshing product from the manway area during normal switching activities in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 210095 was cordoned-off in the railyard. The closest BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder from Amarillo, TX was notified and responded. The responder inspected UTLX 210095 and reported finding 6 of 8 manway securement bolts less than tool tight (from 2 to 3 turns loose). The intact manway cover seal numbered B-635856 was removed and the manway gasket was inspected. The manway gasket was in the correct position and no defects noted. The manway was closed and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. A new seal numbered BNSF HAZMAT 002472 was applied to the manway cover. No ground impact of product was evident and all spillage on the tank car shell evaporated. Response was concluded at 2115 hrs. CST, 1/07/09.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The shipper tendered container, SEAU172026-7/ANC091097, to Horizon Lines in Anchorage for transit to Kodiak. The shipper was notified and corrective action was taken to allow the shipment to make the vessel, Horizon Anchorage/AZ742S.
column169: The shipper must review all shipments to make sure that their documentation matches the actual shipped materials. This must be done prior to tendering it to the carrier(s).

column168: During switching activities in the railyard, GATX 15765 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported with a product splash emanating from this tank car's top fitting area. A BNSF train crew member standing nearby was splattered with product droplets on his cheek and clothing. The employee immediately washed off the impacted facial area and wiped down his clothing. No injury was incurred. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 15765 and found an open orifice atop the valve housing plate that should have been sealed with a 2 1/2 inch pipe plug. Other valve orifices were flanged closed atop this valve housing plate. Since no valves were atop the valve housing plate, no valve housing cover was present. The responder applied a new 2 1/2 inch pipe plug into the open orifice. Once the plug was tool tightened the valve housing plate was completely sealed and secured. Securement was completed by 1016 hrs. CST, 1/10/09. The shipper arranged for a contractor to wipe product spillage from GATX 15765. No ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: 8 small butane aerosols and 2 1 gallon cans flammable paint discovered while shipment underwent security screening.  Jeff Deitz and Gary Meaders, local FAA hazmat agents were notified.

column168: Abenaqui Carrier Driver was exiting Route 3 to enter the Fieldstone QuickStop. When pulling into the driveway the right rear tires of tractor went over a snow packed culvert causing the propane he pulling to rock, snapping off the king pin of the trailer resulting in the loaded tanker to roll onto its side. There was no leakage of product and tank integrity remained intack. Only leakage was hydraulic oil from broken lines which snapped when tank rolled. Local police and fire department arrived on scene, cordoned off area and closed Route 3 until an empty tank arrived to transfer the product prior to the tow company uprighting tanker. There was no issues transfering product which was delivered to Consignee without expception. Both tractor and trailer were towed to local yard for inspection and repair.
column169: Road and parking lot were snow packed with tall snow banks. It was difficult to determine that a road hazard was present when pulling into the driveway. Superior tank construction prevented a catastrophic event.

column168: Driver indicated that he was travelling 50-55 mph going Westbound on Interstate 70 in Univar straight Box Truck 20419 when he felt a “bump” and he looked in his mirror and saw lights right beside his truck as the Univar vehicle started to slide toward the guide rail.  The truck continued to slide over the top of the guide rail and down an embankment (drop of approximately 12-15 feet).  At the bottom of the embankment the truck apparently flipped over on its roof and slid an additinoal 50 feet until it stopped.  Despite severe vehicle damage to the cab, the driver was able to exit the cab and climb up to the Interstate where he flagged a motorist down for assistance.  The box was heavily damaged ejecting a number of the containers including 6 chlorine cylinders and a drum of potassium permangante.  An Emergency Response Contractor (Weavertown Envioronmental) was called to assist with the cleanup and a team was also dispatched from the branch to assist the contractor.    The response personnel removed the cylinders (not leaking) and overpacked the drum of which was clear of the truck.  The emergency response contractor then had to pump the fuel out of the saddle tanks before the truck could be rolled over to prevent possible leakage.  A wrecker was then positioned to pull the truck over onto its side off of the rest of the damaged freight.    When the material under the truck was accessible it was noted that one of the IBC's of sodium hydroxide (caustic soda 30%) solution had been pierced by a portion of the separated metal e-track load securement device.  Spill residues and contaminated soil were collected into roll off containers for transporation to an appropriate TSDF.     180-200 gallons of 30% caustic soda (solution)leaked from the IBC.  This product contaminated the bags of potassium chloride and the soil directly beneath the vehicle.  The caustic did not leave the area of the crash.  There was a creek in the area that was checked periodically during the incident for any evidence of product reaching the water and none was noted.  The vendor placed boom between  the accident scene and the creek when they arrived on site.  Under the direction of a PA DEP Emergency Response specialist at the site, the cleanup vendor removed the contaminated solid, crash debris and potassium chloride from the crash site and placed into two roll off containers which are currently awaiting analysis and   disposal. column168: On January 6th, our driver Victor Villegas was traveling southbound on Interstate 55 in Waggoners, Illinois. At approximately 7:30am, the weather was a wintry mix. It was raining/snowing and the roads were icing up. There was an accident ahead of our driver because of the bad weather. Mr.   Villegas then got on the brakes to slow down in order to avoid getting collected up in the accident. When he did this, he hit a patch of ice and the tractor and trailer jack knifed. The trailer ended up in the center   median lying partially on its side.   The trailer (which was a compartment trailer) had product leaking out of 3 of the 4 compartments. The Montgomery County Haz-mat team responded to the scene and tightened all of the ears around the   domes, this eliminated what was leaking out of the trailer. Prior to the Haz Mat team getting there buckets and temporary pools were set up underneath the dome areas to contain whatever product came out of the domes. The products that leaked were Butyl Carbitol Solvent and Glycol Ether Acetate. It is estimated that about 70 gallons of product leaked out of the trailer. The responders recovered approximately 50 gallons. The remaining product remained in the center median and was collected into absorbent rags or went into the ground. HMHTTC was called into trans-load the material from one trailer into another and they also took care of cleaning up the area. They worked with the Illinois EMA office when they did the clean up.
column169: THE DRIVER RETURNED BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND WENT THROUGH REFRESHER TRAINING AND WAS TERMINATED.  HE WENT THROUGH TRAINING ON DRIVING IN EXTREME WEATHER AND HOW TO PROPERLY INSPECT A TRAILER.  IN THE END THIS SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE THE DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL OF THE EARS IN THE DOME AREA WERE PROPERLY FASTENED.  THIS EVENT WILL BE DISCUSSED AT OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING AND USED AS A LEARNING TOOL.

column168: Driver was attempting to retain a product sample from the trailer's bottom outlet.  The driver first opened the trailer internal valve. Than he slowley started to open   the external valve. As he was slowley turning the valve handle the produck would not flow he than opened the valve some more than there was a rush of material that over shot the spill bucket and onto the concrete pad. Driver quickly closed the valve and tried again. the spilled material quickly evaporated.
column169: The driver failed to follow proceedure as he was trained. he should have had the spill bucket up off the ground and at the product discharge line. When he could not get product to flow through the external valve he should have stopped and closed the internal valve first that try to oped the external valve again. The gasket on the external valve can sometines stick to the valve seat and can suddenly pop open leaving an wider gap between the gasket and the seat than intended and allowing the product to flow faster. Drivers are trained to prepair for such an event.    The driver was disciplined per company policy.

APPLIED SODIUM BARCARBONATE AT THE SCENE TO NEUTRALIZE, AND BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER. ONCE AT PSC, WE DISCOVERED A BATTERY INSIDE THE BOX THAT WAS CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID. WE THEN TOOK STEPS TO EMPTY THE ACID FROM THE BATTERY AND NEUTRALIZE IT. THEN WE FOLLOWED DMP PROCEDURES.

column168: The package was unloaded from the ULD when it was determined that the outermost box was ripped and torn. The box was made of rice paper and tore easily. The box was set to the side to be rewrapped. As the box was subsequently moved, two of the three batteries fell over so that the positive & negative posts were facing each other. The batteries came in contact with each other, short circuiting and arcing.Sparks were seen shooting from the packaging. The batteries were seperated and righted. The shipper was notified who directed us to destroy it as a hazardouswaste. The box was marked as Non-Spillable Batteries as required by 49CFR 173.159(d) (2) and USG-08 in ICAO. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Tony Ringos in EWR and Hazardous Materials Manager Steven Joseph in New York. FedEx took ten picturesof the shipment and I have sent them via email to FAA Manager Joseph. The freight is on a temporary hold pending an FAA inspection. FedEx has notified the shipper that this product is being embargoed until such time that proper packaging is utilized.

column168: (A)On 01/07/2009 at approximately 09:07 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard in Cincinnati, OH discovered UTLX 951090, a loaded tank car of Liquified Petroleum Gas (butane) was derailed with no leaks. The car was isolated and the shipper, OH EPA (report number 0901-31-0047), and Cincinnati 911, were notified.  The car was found to have been derailed and lying off the tracks on its side.  There were no leaks or releases from the tank car.  The Emergency responders initiated a  loose  mile radius evacuation and restricted traffic flow on 8th avenue and Gest Road in Cincinnati as a precaution.  The roads were intersecting north and south of the derailment respectively. The car was moved after re-railing. The evacuation was lifted at 16:20 hours. There were no leaks or releases from the tank car.  The Emergency responders initiated a  loose  mile radius evacuation and restricted traffic flow on 8th avenue and Gest Road in Cincinnati as a precaution. column168: (A)On January 12, 2009 at 07:34 hours, CSX Transportation, train Q38110 was reported derailed in Defiance, OH, between mileposts BI 91.07 and BI 92.08, Garrett Subdivision, Chicago Division. Cars 1  through 30 with two locomotives were derailed. Defiance, Ohio Fire and Police personnel responded. Hulcher Emergency Services, Inc. and R. J. Corman Company accomplished rerailing and removal of the rail cars. Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Incorporated, Findlay, OH and Arcadis, Columbus, OH responded for CSX Transportation. TILX 191824 was upright and 90 degrees to the tracks with "A" end facing north (towards State Route 24). The tank shell was torn on its "R" side mid tank from the manway cover to the bottom of the tank. The tank shell was indented approximately 7 feet. Approximatley 1 gallon of alcohols, nos was released. ECESI monitored area about this tank car and no indication of flammable environment nor presence of alcohols, nos (VOC) were noted. TILX 191824 was removed from derailment by contractors and placed in holding area adjacent to tracks to be cleaned and purged and scrapped on site.  (B)TILX 191820 was upright, 45 degrees to the tracks with "A" end facing south (towards tracks)  and "B" end facing north (towards State Route 24), spanning a sloped area. The bottom outelt nozzle was sheared off (skid protection intact) and the external ball valve opened one-half turn. Approximatley 1 gallon of alcohols, nos was released. ECESI monitored area about this tank car and no indication of flammable environment nor presence of alcohols, nos (VOC) were noted. TILX 191820 was removed from derailment by contractors and placed in holding area adjacent to tracks to be cleaned and purged and scrapped on site.  (C)TILX 192741 was upright, parallel to the tracks resting on the south side of the tracks. "A" end was facing west. The "A" head was punctured on the "L" side at the sill (6 0'clock postion) and the "R" side of the tank was punctured mid tank (at ladder). Both punctures were approximately 1 - 1.5 feet in diameter.  Approximatley 1 gallon of alcohols, nos was released. ECESI monitored area about this tank car and no indication of flammable environment nor presence of alcohols, nos (VOC) were noted. TILX 192741 was removed from derailment by contractors and placed in holding area adjacent to tracks to be cleaned and purged and scrapped on site.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 01/08/09, CSXI accepted hazardous material shipping instructions from Mediterranean Shipping Co. for MEDU 244010 from Elizabeth Marine Terminal, NJ to Portland, OR. The shipper's original bill of lading contained one hazardous material commodity - Alcohols, N.O.S. (Ethanol), 3, UN1987, PG III.  The shipment arrived via rail at CSXI Chicago terminal in Bedford Park, IL, and was transported via truck to the BNSF terminal to continue its move to destination.  The BNSF rejected the shipment back to CSXI because the applied placards were too low on the sides of the container.  A copy of the bill of lading was requested from Mediterranean Shipping Co. Upon review of the provided bill of lading, it was discovered that there was a product listed on the bill of lading that was not declared on the original shipping instructions provided to CSXI. The undeclared commodity is Turpentine Substitute, 3, UN 1300, III.  CSXI contacted Mediterranean Shipping Co. regarding the discrepancy.  Mediterranean states that it was a clerical error on their part.  CSXI has updated its shipping document (waybill) to include the previously undeclared hazardous material commodity and the shipment has been released to continue to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening the trailer doors, it was discovered that three (3) 55-gallon drums had fell over during transit.  The trailer was isolated and TAS Environmental Services, Inc. of San Antonio, Texas was dispatched to investigate the trailer and perform the cleanup.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. donned the proper personal protective equipment and proceeded to investigate the trailer.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. determined that a pallet broke during transit, and that a nail from the pallet punctured one of the drums.  Approximately 4 gallons of free product were released and impacted the trailer floor.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. performed the cleanup using absorbent material and absorbent pads. The cleanup materials, impacted pallet, personal protective equipment, and leaking drum were placed into three over pack drums.  TAS Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the cleanup.

column168: The package was found spilling in a FedEx truck.  The package was isolated placed in a salvage drum and the spilled material was recovered too.  During the investigation, it was found that the shipment was offered as an Excepted Quantity of Methanol, UN 1230.  In fact the quantity far exceeded the 30ml allowable amount and there was no Methanol in the package.  Instead it was found to be a 10% Formalin Solution.  It was also determined that the shipper had been trained to offer Infectious Substances and Dry Ice only.  Training could not be verified for Excepted Quantities or other hazard classes.  The package had no absorbent nor cushioning material.  The driver, Eric Poland, complained of irraitation to his eyes, nose and throat.  He sought medical attention at a local emergency clinic.  Mr. Poland was cleared for full duty for the following business day.  It was initially reported that FAA SA Beth Romo was present at the FedEx station when the incident occurred.  In fact that was false as SA Romo had stopped by the FedEx Ramp that evening.  As I was working under the pretense that FAA had knowledge of the incident, we allowed the shipment to be reclaimed by the shipper before pictures could be taken.  The FAA was notified, I spoke to both HazMat Mgr Bryan Buchanan & SA Beth Romo.

IAPX 1053 (DOT 113A90W tank car) was reported venting in the railyard from its side operating compartment. IAPX 1053 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection by a shipper mechanical responder. The shipper responder reported finding a small crack in the stainless steel piping leading to the drain valve (liquid line/discharge valve). The responder reduced the internal pressure within IAPX 1053 and applied a wet cloth patch (freeze patch) with securement tape around the cracked pipe to seal the crack. Afterwards, the venting ceased and IAPX 1053 was released to proceed to its destination.

column168: GATX 29955 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported sloshing product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and GATX 29955 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting responder inspection. BNSF contract responders reported finding 3 of 6 manway securement bolts hand tight. Responders opened the manway cover for gasket and product outage inspection. The product outage level and the manway gasket were deemed appropriate. All other valves and fittings were inspected and deemed secure. The manway cover was closed and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. Securement was completed by approximately 1615 hrs. MST, 1/18/09. The spillage on the tank shell that didn't evaporate was wiped. No ground impact from product spillage was evident. No further product release was observed from GATX 29955 during subsequent rail movements.

column168: UTLX 200376 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 200376 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting responder inspection. BNSF contract responders reported finding liquid product seeping out at the 3 inch liquid valve's closure plug. The liquid valve handle was not attached and the responders found the valve slightly open with its closure plug not tool tight. The liquid valve was also loose at its threaded connection but did not leak at this orifice. The liquid valve was removed and thread sealant applied. While the valve was off, the product outage was checked and it was deemed appropriate. The liquid valve was reapplied in its closed position along with its closure plug, also with new thread sealant. Both were tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were inspected and deemed secure. The spillage on the tank shell that didn't evaporate was wiped. A small area of impacted soil/ballast under UTLX 200376 was shoveled into a five gallon bucket for appropriate future disposal. No further product release was observed from UTLX 200376 during subsequent rail movements.  Intact Suncor seals removed numbered 124151 and 124152. They were replaced by seals numbered TIS 5820 and TIS 5821.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: GATX 68603 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the top manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped. Later, GATX 68603 was carefully moved to a mechanical repair track in the railyard awaiting responder inspection. BNSF contract responders observed liquid product that was hardening on the mid-side tank shell and side ladder. The spillage emanated from the manway cover. All six manway securement bolts were found to be less than tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and it appeared to be deteriorated or worn. This combination of loose manway cover securement and a faulty gasket prevented a good seal at the manway nozzle/cover closure. Product outage appeared appropriate. The responders applied a new Salco neoprene gasket and properly secured/tool tightened the manway securement bolts. All other valves and fittings were checked and found secure. The spillage on the tank shell (top and side) and side ladders were wiped down and cleaned off as much as possible. No significant ground impact atop the soil/ballast under GATX 68603 was observed. No further product release was observed from GATX 68603 during subsequent rail movements.  Intact Murphy Oil seals removed numbered 40176 and 40185. They were replaced by seals numbered TIS 5822 and TIS 5823.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: USE DUNNAGE AND AIR BAGS TO BLOCK AND BRACE. PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHENLOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALSMUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS ANDDRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYECHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SALOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMSOF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOPI USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEENLAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.OF

column168: The forklift driver was in the process of unloading a pallet of four drums. When the driver raised the pallet of drums to exit the trailer one of the drums struck a supporting screw to the securement device that extended out from the trailer wall. This resulted in a small leak to the upper chime of the container. Upon noticing the leak the forklift driver placed the drum on it's side to stop the leak.
column169: A review of the incident was conducted by facility personnel. It was determined that the securement device fastner/screw needed to be reconfigured so that it would not extend off the wall of the trailer. A formal complaint was documented and sent to the carrier for their response. Additional training has been provided to affected employees to inspect all future inbound and outbound trailers for any obstructions that may cause damage.

column168: Further investigation revealed the origin terminal Winchester, VA did not proper load the product on the trailer. When the shipment arrived at the Elkton, MD HUB facility, it was found leaking on the tail of the trailer. The freight was loaded on the tail of the trailer and a visual inspection of the carton revealed the carton was wet. Further inspection of the carton’s contents revealed small dents in 2 of the 4 cans and a small fracture to the bottom seam of the leaking can resulting in ¾ of 1 gallon to be released. There was no visible evidence of impact to the carton i.e. freight on or fallen around the shipment.  The outer carton has a small crease in the bottom quarter of the package on the long side (pictures attached). Loading of hazardous materials or small liquid shipments on the tail of the trailer is not an approved practice of Estes Express Lines. The containers not affected were recouped, properly loaded, protected and moved on for delivery to the consignee in Bridgeport, CT on 1/30/2009. The release was managed in 20 minutes and the released product was placed in a recovery area. Pictures were taken of the carton and the contents on 02/06/2009 to try and determine the cause of the damage. The product was replaced into a recovery container and is waiting for disposition from Dupont.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver stopped at Clean Harbor's 10 day in-transit storage location in order to transfer the shipment onto a seond vehicle for continued transportation.  When facility p[ersonnel opened the trailer door, they identified  a petroleum odor.  The emergency response plan was activated and dock personnel were removed from the area while an assesment was made.  Using appropriate personal protective equipment, the trailer was entered and it was determined that approximately 2 gallons of material had been released from a crack that developed in the top clsoure of the container.  Formal notification was made pursuant to the facility's operating permit and an in-house response was initiated.  Facility personnel placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum along with all material used to absorb all freee liquids and clean the trailer floor.  This container was then placed on the vehicle for continued transportation.
column169: AT the time the container was accepted for transportation, the driver inspected the container and did not see evidence of a leak.  The condition of the drum, however, did show evidence of rust.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been instructed to condut a thorough container inspection prior to accepting non-bulk packages for transportation and take those steps necessary to address any containers that show evidence of excessive rus that could impact the structural integrity of a container during incidents normally encounted during transportation.

column168: On January 27th at 12:50 hours, FRA Inspector David Snyder, was performing an inspection at the CSXT Davis Yard Facility in Wilmington, NC.  During that inspection, he discovered UTLX85135, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from top of the railcar.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Colonial Terminals was notified.  Colonial Terminals dispatched a response crew to the scene and found that the manway cover gasket was deteriorated. Colonial representatives replaced the manway cover gasket and decontaminated the exterior of the car.  The tank car was secured and released to destination.      An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not required for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  209  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: While being switched in the KCS Port Arthur, TX yard, KCS ground employee was splashed with hazmat lading released from the manway closure. The KCS employee immediately washed the material off and did not report an injury. The Shipper, Huntsman Petrochemical, responded to the yard and assessed this car.  Shipper responders found a loose, improperly tightened, manway closure. The Huntsman responders corrected the release by properly tightening the manway closure.  Huntsman responders advised the exposed employee that this material would not harm him.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shippers are requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the causes of this release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.

column169: PACKAGAING FAILURE. BETTER PACKAGES. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PRODUCTS, USING PAILS, DRUMS AND OR BAGS, CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS, ARE PROPERLY AND SAFELY SEALED AND CLOSED TO ENSURE NO RELEASE. IN ADDITION THE PACKAGING MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE DURABILITY OF PAILS, DRUMS AND OR BAGS MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS AND POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUBE BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN LOADING NOT THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: 128 THREE AND ONE HALF GALLON PAILS IN 4 PLYWOOD BOXES WERE NOTICED TO HAVE A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TRL.  AFTER CALLING CHEMICAL DEPT WITH SHIPMENT INFORMATION, TXR OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO DISCOVER WET TRAILER FLOOR.  TXR UNHOOKED THE SET AND BACKED TRAILER TO THE DOCK AND REMOVED THE 4 CRATES TO INVESTIGATE DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE PAILS HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS FROM ITS CLOSURE.  THERE WERE NO PUNCTURES TO ANY OF THE PAILS.  TXR REMOVED THE PAIL, PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG AND SEALED AND THEN PLACED IN SMALL HAZ DRUM.  THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT WILL SHIP FROM TXR.
column169: THERE MUST HAVE BEEN SOME WEAKNESS IN THE PAILS CLOSURE CAUSING LEAKAGE. THERE ARE NO PUNCTURE'S IN THE PAIL, NO DAMAGE THAT WE CAN DETECT TO ANY OF THIS SHIPMENT. SIMPLY PACKAGE FAILURE IN MY OPINION.

column168: Under Quality Distribution claim number 24369, a tanker carrying tetrahydrofuran was observed to have the potential to leak. Driver was going to transfer product from our cargo tank to customer storage tank.  He started the product flowing slowly to check the line for any problems or leaks.  He discovered that the PVC fitting on the customer fill line was leaking into a bucket that the he had put under it.   He shut down, tried to tighten the fitting and attempted to unload again.  It still leaked so driver shut down again.  As the driver was closing the customer valve then, the fitting broke off completely and product from the hose started spilling out.  Most went in the bucket with less than a gallon going on the ground.  Driver used spill pads on the spill. driver alerted the customer and they were having maintenance come out to fix it.
column169: Driver was instructed to make sure the fitting is fixed properly or replaced before attempting to offload again.

The driver was unloading diesel fuel into an above ground storage tank at a petroleum distibution bulk plant when the spill occurred. He was using the PTO powered pump on the tractor. After making all connections and strarting to pump the product, the driver saw product on the ground near the tractor. The driver investigated and found that he had left a petcock valve open on the pump. This small valve is used to vent air into the line when draining hoses. He stopped unloading, closed the valve, called for assistance, and then finished unloading. A spill contractor was called to remove the contaminated gravel and replace it with new gravel. The spill did not leave the property and did not enter any drains or waterway. It was confined to the gravel lot/raodway in the bulk plant.

column168: Driver was heading south on US Hwy 521 out of Lancaster, SC and failed to reduce speed enough while making a right turn onto Twilight Road causing the tanker to overturn on the south side of Twilight road.  The Driver was pulled to safety by a local businessman before the tanker caught fire.  It is not known where the initial release occured but there were reports from people at the scene that product was coming out of the airspace between the double bulkhead between compartments #4 and #5 which would mean one of those bulkheads cracked and product entered the airspace and vented to the outside since it is an open area.  The Fire Department allowed the unit to keep burning for several hours to mitigate the environmental damage.  Only a small portion of the shell that was in contact with the ground was left after the fire was extinguished.  Vacuum truck and dikes were utilizied on the south (lower) of the unit to prevent any runoff from the product and firefighting efforts. The unit was removed and hwy 521 was reopened.  Over the next several days contaminated soil was excavated and backfilled with clean material.
column169: Driver was terminated  Cover this topic at future safety meetings    It would apprear that the design of double bulkhead trailers be changed so that the airspace between compartments be sealed and some type of probe system installed to let you know if any product is leaking between compartments instead of being open to the outside.

column168: Damage to IBC was discovered as it was being unloaded on the dock.  The top of the IBC had a small crack in it that looked as if it had split.  The safety Department was called and so was the emergency response telephone number on the bill of lading.  The shipper was contacted the obtain an MSDS on the material in the IBC.  Acid neutralizer was used on the small amount of liquid that was released in the trailer.  Due to the crack looking like a split in the plastic, and the IBC being properly blocked and braced, and nothing loaded on top, it appeared as if the crack was caused by the material and package freezing, although this is just an estimate. The temperature during transportation and the material sitting on the dock was well below freezing. The identification markings on the tote are very long, and may not all be required on question 26a, however, everything on the packaging identification sticker has been entered on this question just to make sure.
column169: If the crack is determined to have been caused by the material freezing, then the shipper will be notified that their package was inadequate.  However, if it is determined that a loading error occurred, and an employee was responsible for the damage, then this employee will be retrained in proper loading procedures and disciplined per company policy.

column168: When material handler moved a shipment that was staged on the dock he observed a small puddle of liquid underneath the valve assembly of an IBC that was staged next to the shipment on the dock. Further investigation discovered that the pallet that was staged next to the IBC on the dock must have slightly hit the bottom valve handle on the IBC to the open position resulting in the unintentional release of the residue product that remained in the IBC. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and valve handle was positioned in the closed position to prevent further spillage.
column169: In past experiences with incidents such as these - it always seems to happen because the valve handle sticks out beyond the confines of the IBC down at the bottom. Yes, our material handlers should be paying attention to their clearances and be on the alert of these protruding valve handles - but I just wish that there was some way these valve handles could be protected better at the bottom discharge lines or be required to be with in the confines of the IBC to prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: At approximately 9:15pm on 1/22/09 our driver notified us that he had a caustic spill on Horton Rd leading from the plant.  Not sure of amount of the spill we called 911 to request a Emergency Hazmat Team to respond. At 9:22pm Lt Bo Nicholson with the Gordon Co Fire Dept Hazmat Team arrived and took charge. At 9:24pm we contacted GAEPD. At 9:35pm we contacted Marion Evironmental who arrived at 11:00 and commenced the clean up at 12 mid-night. At 1:30am due to the freezing roadway Lt Nicholson instructed Marion Evironmental to place cones around spill area and to return the next morning to continue clean up. At 9:30am 1/23/09 clean up commenced again and Marion Evironmental used dilute sulfuric acid to neutralize the caustic. They then applied absorbent materials and sweep up the area to dispose of all material.  Marion Evironmental estimated the spill to be between 25 - 50 gallons.  The RQ for 50% sodium hydroxide is 156 gallons. Our investigation determined that on 1/22/09 a plant employee failed to secure the dome lid on the tanker after trying to remove the freezing caustic in the tanker. It was also determined that the driver failed to perform as complete pre-trip and secure the lid after hooking up to this tanker.  As he left the plant some of the unfrozen caustic spilled out of the dome.
column169: Retraining on all tanker drivers on relief valves/pressure/pre-trips including our in house checklist.  Disciplinary action taken with this driver for failure to utilize the mandatory checklist required by the company for tanker drivers prior to leaving the plant. - He received a 3 day suspension  Training done on plant employees involved with tanker truck loading and on the securement of products including tankers within the plant

column168: This report explains 2 separate incidents for the same shipment.    Phase I occurred on January 30, 2009. The shipment was loaded from Winchester, VA (origin) through Greensboro where it was transferred to move to Houston. The Greensboro terminal stacked another shipment on top of the cartons of paint. In transit the top of 1 of the cans was crushed causing a release of .5 LGA that was recognized U/A at the Dallas terminal. The Dallas terminal took 2 cans of paint that were affected by the release (1 crushed and 1 contaminated), and placed them in a suitable recovery container and moved the shipment onto Houston for delivery in Beaumont, TX. The release was managed in approximately 45 minutes.     Phase II occurred on February 2, 2009. Dallas loaded the shipment on the tail of the trailer for Houston. During transit a valve that was not properly blocked or braced fell on the carton previously recouped at the Dallas terminal. U/A to Houston, the product was noticed leaking. All the product from the 2 gallons contained in the carton had been released as the lids popped off due to the impact of the valve. In both incidents the product was contained in the carriers trailer. The product was properly recovered and placed in a UN approved container and will disposed of properly according to regulations. No human exposures occurred during either release. The release was managed in approximately 60 minutes.

A BNSF unit sulfur train operating on UPRR main track derailed 18 loaded tank cars. The cause of the derailment was attributed to a broken rail. AMOX 13231 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side. Impact with the ground damaged 5 of 8 manway securement swing bolts (3 detached and 2 bent), causing the manway securement to loosen. A small amount of product escaped from the loosened manway closure. The product spillage rapidly solidified and self-sealed the manway closure. AMOX 13231 was uprighted and spillage on the ground was shoveled into a recovery roll-off box for solid waste landfill disposal. Equipment damage to AMOX 13231 necessitated product transfer. The remaining product within AMOX 13231 was heated and transferred into another suitable tank car.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF road switcher making up an outbound train in the railyard shoved railcars into the wrong yard track after the conductor inadvertently lined the switch incorrectly. This resulted in a derailment of 14 railcars when the shoved railcars collided with railcars on the switching lead. DBUX 207791 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) the first railcar in the shove movement derailed on its side with a slow drip of product emanating from its manway closure. BNSF contract responders tighten the manway securement bolts on DBUX 207791 in an attempt to stop the product dripping at the manway cover/nozzle closure. This effort significantly reduced the product drips. Responders constructed an earthen poly lined berm to contain the dripping product impacting the ground. DBUX 207791 was uprighted which ended any further product release. Granular absorbent was applied atop the impacted soil/ballast to solidify the spillage. Afterwards, the impacted soil/ballast was shoveled into 55 gallon recovery drums for appropriate waste disposal. Equipment damage to DBUX 207791 necessitated product transfer to another suitable tank car. DBUX 207791 was then scheduled to be cleaned and purged of hazardous material.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO BECOME EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM; LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Freezing
column168: At the start of the workday on 1/28/09, The Gas Company, LLC’s (TGC) tanker driver performed his pre-trip inspection, hose and remote shutoff tests on his tanker.  The driver then filled his tanker and completed his first 7 deliveries.  For his 8th delivery, he was reversing up the driveway when he heard a loud “pop” which seemed to come from under his tanker and saw a white mist coming from behind the tanker’s cab.  He immediately drove the tanker out of the driveway, parked it on the side of the road, and turned off the engine.  He got out to investigate and saw LPG leaking near the pump area.  He could not pinpoint the leak because of poor visibility due to the white mist and ice that had formed around the pump and internal valve.  He called TGC’s Maui office to report the incident.  The driver attempted to close the internal valve but the LPG kept coming out.  He set up cones and triangles about 100 feet in both directions and directed pedestrians and vehicles away from the tanker.      The Maui Fire Department (MFD) arrived on scene and established a command post at a shopping center parking lot nearby.  In the interim, TGC had dispatched an empty tanker to the site to remove the LPG from the malfunctioning tanker.  MFD instructed TGC not to transfer any LPG until the State Airport’s foam truck arrived.  When the foam truck arrived, TGC’s leadman checked the actuator under the tank and found it to be in the closed position.  As it was then determined that the LPG could not be removed from the leaking tanker, the decision was made, after discussions with the Incident Commander (MFD), to tow the truck to an isolated area.  Once towed, TGC’s crew setup a flare to burn off the propane in the tanker with the MFD fire truck standing by.  When the tanker’s liquid level gauge reached 40%, a brass hammer was used to hit the fisher valve, causing it to close, stopping the LPG from leaking.      The tanker was brought back to TGC’s Maui baseyard for inspection and repairs.  A 1/8” gap between the pump and the flange was noted, which is suspected to be where the LPG leaked.  The gap was created by the loose bolts on the intake port of the pump.    TGC estimates the duration of the release was approximately 9 hours.
column169: 1.  Review the procedures and history of the tanker to try and determine how or why the bolts were loose.    2.  Evaluate feasibility of installing another valve under the tanker instead of a plug, to provide an emergency alternative to transfer LPG, if needed.    3.  Contact tanker manufacturer to discuss whether there are any feasible alterations to insure that the internal valve operates properly and whether there is a better way to secure the bolts so that it will be harder for them to come loose.

column168: HERITAGE EMPLOYEES WERE UNLOADING A VAN TRAILER FULL OF CONTAINERS.  THE FIRST CONTAINER THAT WAS UNLOADED WAS A WOODEN CRATE LABELED AS RQ, UN2809, WAS MERCURY, 8, PG III, (MERCURY DEVICES), (D009), ERG#172.  THIS CRATE WAS PLACED INTO THE STAGING ARE INSIDE THE BUILDING.  AFTER THE REMAINING CONTAINERS ON THE VAN WERE UNLOADED, EMPLOYEES NOTICED THAT ELEMENTAL MERCURY HAD LEAKED FROM THE WOODEN CRATE INTO THE STAGING ARE AND IN THE TRAILER.  MERCURY WAS REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING UTILIZING A MERCURY SPILL CLEAN-UP KIT.  MERCURY WAS ALSO REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER BY REMOVING AND REPLACING THE WOODEN FLOOR.  MERCURY VAPOR LEVELS WERE MONITORED IN THE STAGING AREA AND IN THE TRAILER PRIOR TO CLEAN-UP, DURING CLEAN-UP AND POST CLEAN-UP.  THE WOODEN CRATE WAS OPENED, INSPECTED AND REPACKAGED.  IMPROPER CONTAINER TYPE AND PACKAGING APPEARS TO BE THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.  THE WOODEN CRATE CONTAINED MANOMETER-LIKE DEVICES WITH ELEMENTAL MERCURY.  TUBES ON THESE DEVICES APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CUR AND LOOSELY DUCT-TAPED.  THE DEVICES WERE LAYING INSIDE THE CRATE WITH NO OTHER INNER PACKAGING MATERIAL.  IT APPEARS THE MERCURY LEAKED FROM THE LOOSELY SEALED TUBES AND THROUGH THE SEAMS OF THE WOODEN CRAFTE, AS THE DEVICES AND THE CRATE WERE OTHERWISE INTACT AND UNBROKEN.  NO INJURIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AND MERCURY BLOOD LEVELS OF ALL POTENTIALLY EXPOSED EMPLOYEES WERE BELOW DETECTION LIMITS.
column169: HERITAGE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE GENERATOR OF THE MATERIAL TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT, PROPER PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS AND NECESSARY CLEAN-UP.  A HERITAGE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION REPORT WAS ALSO DISTRIBUTED TO ALL HERITAGE LOCATIONS FOR REVIEW.

column168: Plant Operator tapped "A" side valve, and had a minor release of vapor at the gasket of less than 1 pound. Driver closed valve with no further incident, and immediately called supervisor for further direction. It was decided to off load from the "B' side, which was carried out with no further incident. The defective gasket was replaced. No evacuations were made, and no injuries were reported.

Driver had just made a left turn onto Lake Drive. At this time the front passenger tire traveled into a small snow bankthat bordered a ditch. The truck got sucked into the ditch. When the truck came to a complete stop it fell on its passenger side causing a small propane leak in the hose going to the swivel on the hose reel. The road is in a private development and is narrow. At the time of the accident, the road was snow packed covered and slippery.The ditch that the truck was in is about three feet deep and about six feet wide with no guide rail.The driver reported the incident immediately and we responded and got to the scene within 10 minutes. Upon arrival we made certain that the driver was all right. In which he was. Then we contained the small leak that was limited to the swivel hose. At this point the fire department and the two wreckers arrived. We then vented the propane from the hose into a wooded area with a spray of water from the fire department. The duration of the small leak was about one half hour. The truck was then safe to be lifted up on its wheels by the two wreckers. The truck was then towed back to our plant where all necessary repairs were made.There was no damage to the cargo tank, piping or valves. The small leak was limited to the swivel hose that connects to the hose reel. No diesel fuel, motor oil or antifreeze was released.
column169: Always remain focused on the task at hand. Beware of all surroundings at all times. Determine if a road is safe to be driven on and most of all keep your eyes focused on the road that you are traveling on.

At that time the driver and operator observed the storage tank overflow as the overflow line to the storage tank came outside the building. The driver then immediately shut off his internal valve to stop the flow of product. It was discovered that the crossover line to fill both storage tanks was not letting the product cross over to the other tank as a nitrogen blanket was not releasing as fast as product was flowing into the storage tanks.
column169: I feel that customer recieving product with any type of perssure on their storage tanks, should release the pressure before off loading to prevent any type of damage to unloading lines, hoses or trying to have product flow from one tank to another.

column169: INSPECT AREAS THOROUGHLY TO ENSURE UNSAFE CONDITIONS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGING OR PUNCTURING  TO PACKAGES OF DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS. PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF LIQUIDS. CHECK TRAILER FLOORS AND DOCK AREAS TO ENSURE SHARP EDGES, WOOD PIECES, NAILS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGES OR INJURIES. CHEMICAL AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT FROM BEING DAMAGED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT OR SHARP AND POINTED OBJECTS, SUCH AS A NAIL. USE DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD, MW PALLETS AND OR AIRBAGS TO PROPERLY SHROUD, BLOCK, BRACE AND SECURE FREIGHT AND THE ENTIRE LOAD. column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering fuel to a client location. The underground storage tank was overfilled and ULSD fuel leaked out of the tank into the adjacent concrete driveway. Approximately 85 gallons was spilled. The path of the fuel reached the soil and ran down a steep embankment into a stormwater inlet box. The fuel continued through an underground drain pipe and on to a drainage ditch. As a result of low rainfall levels the fuel did not enter or flow towards the Yellow River just west of the location. SWS responded to the spill and utilized an industrial vacuum, removing product and water. Soil remediation was done in the area affected by the spill. The stormwater drain was also cleaned out and vacuumed. Following all cleanup and remediation SWS returned to the site to backfill and restore the site.

column168: ON JANUARY 29, 2009 A SINGLE AXLE PROPANE GAS DELIVERY TRUCK OWNED BY BOUTWELL GAS CO. OF FOREST, MISS. WAS HEADING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 35 NEAR THE FOREST MISS. CITY LIMITS WHEN, AFTER TOPPING A HILL THE DRIVER CAME UPON TWO NORTHBOUND CARS STOPPED IN THE HIGHWAY.  THE LEAD CAR WAS STOPPED AND WAITING FOR ONCOMING TRAFFIC TO PASS BEFORE TURNING LEFT INTO A DRIVEWAY.  THE DRIVER OF THE PROPANE TRUCK NOT HAVING TIME TO STOP, VERRED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD TO AVOID HITTING THE TWO STOPPED CARS.  AFTER PASSING THE TWO CARS THE PROPANE TRUCK DRIVER THEN ATTEMPTED TO STEER BACK ON THE HIGHWAY BUT THE ATTEMPT RESULTED IN THE PROPANE TRUCK OVERTURNING AND COMING TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE, HALF ON AND HALF OFF OF THE HIGHWAY.  THERE WAS NO CONTACT WITH THE OTHER TWO VEHICLES BUT THERE WAS DAMAGED TO THE PROPANE TRUCK WHICH RESULTED IN A PROPANE GAS LEAK FROM A DAMAGED FITTING NEAR THE METER AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER OF THE PROPANE TRUCK RECEIVED ONLY MINOR BURSES AND NO ONE ELSE WAS INVOLVED.  BECAUSE OF THE PROPANE LEAK WHICH OCCURRED NEAR THE METER AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK, POLICE AND HIGHWAY PATROL AUTHORITIES DECIDED TO CLOSE THE HIGHWAY UNTIL THE LEAK COULD BE STOPPED AND WRECKED TRUCK TOWED AWAY.  AFTER HAVING BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT, FOUR BOUTWELL GAS CO. EMPLOYEES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  EVENTUALLY AN INSPECTOR WITH THE L C GAS DIVISION OF THE MISS. STATE FIRE MARSHAL'S OFFICE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO OFFER ADVICE.  AFTER SOME DIFFICULTY IN FINDING THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND THE CORRECT VALVE TO TURN OFF THE GAS SUPPLY, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED IN ABOUT TWO HOURS.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN SET UPRIGHT AND TOWED AWAY IN A TOTAL OF ABOUT THREE HOURS AFTER THE WRECK OCCURRED.  HIGHWAY 35 WAS THEN REOPENED.  WHAT PROPANE LEAKED OUT EVAPORATED WITHIN MINUTES AND WAS NOT A SAFETY FACTOR AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE PROPANE TRUCK AND TANK CHASSIS WERE LATER DETERMINED TO BE "TOTALED" BY THE INSURANCE COMPANY.  THOUGH THE TANK ITSELF WAS NOT LEAKING, IT DID SUSTAIN A DENT THAT WOULD HAVE BEEN EXPENSIVE TO REPAIR.
column169: IN RESPONSE TO THE PROPANE TRUCK ACCIDENT OF 1/29/2009, THE TRUCK DRIVER RESPONSIBLE WAS PERMANENTLY REMOVED FROM DRIVING SERVICE.  WHILE BOUTWELL GAS COMPANY HAS HIGH SAFETYY STANDARDS, THIS DRIVER WAS NOT ADHERING TO COMPANY SAFE DRIVING STANDARDS.  SUBSEQUENT IN-HOUSE SAFETY MEETINGS HAVE FOCUSED ON THIS ACCIDENT AND SAFET DRIVING PRACTICES TO BE FOLLOWED BY COMPANY DRIVERS.

column168: On January 13, 2009, at 4:00 p.m., a Bork Transport chemical delivery truck spilled Sodium Hydroxide 40%-60% (MSDS attached), in the parking lot of Cintas Corporation, 1025 National Parkway, Schaumburg, IL, 60173. The delivery truck was delivering chemicals to Cintas Corporation. The truck was parked on the North side of the building and the Bork Transport driver was off-loading chemical from the tanker truck into plant tanks. While pumping from one of the truck compartments on his truck to the plant tank, he noticed that another compartment on his truck was frozen. The driver began warming the external valves on the frozen compartment to get the chemical to flow. The valves started to warm up and a slight drip began from the valve. The driver went to secure the hose, but the drip turned into a heavier flow which prevented him from securing the hose. The entire compartment of chemical off-loaded into the Northeast corner of the Cintas Corporation parking lot. The compartment contained 1100 gallons (13640 pounds) of Sodium Hydroxide 40%-60%. John Lavarota, Dober Research Works, witnessed the entire event. Cintas Corporation purchases this chemical from Dober Research Works, who contracts the delivery of the chemical to Bork Transport.   At 4:16 p.m., Jake Resser, Cintas Corporation’s Plant Manager at the Schaumburg location, called 911 and reported both the Hazmat incident as well as potential chemical burns to the driver of the Bork Transport chemical tanker truck. At 4:21 p.m., The Village of Schaumburg Fire Department and The Village of Schaumburg Police Department arrived at Cintas Corporation. At 5:35 p.m. Bork Transport The chemical had completely leaked out of the tanker compartment by this time. The Police Department secured the area of the spill. The Fire Department immediately isolated the chemical and evaluated the extent of spill. They determined that the material had entered a facility storm water drainage and discharges into a ditch across the street They placed hazmat pigs at the end of the drainage ditch to absorb and prevent further migration. The PH was tested on-site by the Fire Department and was determined to be 12.0. There was no impact to the city sanitary sewer or any other storm sewer systems. Hazmat pigs were also placed in the parking lot, even though most of the chemical had already froze on the pavement.   At 5:55 p.m., Jake Resser notified the Illinois EPA of the spill. The case number was H20090037. Mr. Resser spoke to Paul Kattner, who notified him Jim Clark, IEPA Des Plaines, would be in contact with him the following day. At 6:00 p.m., the Schaumburg Fire Department notified the National Response Center. At 6:15 p.m., the Schaumburg Fire Department notified the TEMA to confirm the case number from the JEPA. At 6:20 p.m., Chris Johnson, Hazchem Environmental Corp, and David Gray, Bork Transport, arrived at the scene. At this time, Mr. Gray acknowledged that Bork Transport was at fault of the spill and Bork Transpor
